=========================
TestNG Listener - Notes
=========================

Listener
--------
A Listener is a TestNG feature that listens to test execution events
 and performs actions automatically.

Why do we use Listener?
-----------------------
- Capture screenshots on failure.
- Update Extent Reports.
- Log test execution.
- Avoid writing the same code in every test case.

Implementation
--------------
1. Create a class.
2. Implement the ITestListener interface.
3. Override the required methods.

Example:
public class MyListener implements ITestListener

Common Methods
--------------
onStart()          -> Executes before the test suite starts.
onTestStart()      -> Executes before each test starts.
onTestSuccess()    -> Executes when a test passes.
onTestFailure()    -> Executes when a test fails.
onTestSkipped()    -> Executes when a test is skipped.
onFinish()         -> Executes after all tests complete.

How to Register Listener?
-------------------------
1. Using @Listeners annotation.
2. Using testng.xml (Recommended in Frameworks).

Interview Definition
--------------------
A Listener is a TestNG interface that listens to test execution events
and automatically performs actions such as capturing screenshots,
 logging test results, and updating Extent Reports.